Posted: October 4, 2014
Early Access Review
								//// TL;DR Version ////think of VT like Fallout: New Vegas, except with less original content that came with the initial purchase (you can get more content free at moddb.com, supported by the dev himself). This is due to the number of bugs needed to be fixed since the game revolves around creator content.You can buy now and enjoy what the community has to offer (and still growing). Might not look like much but alike New Vegas, you'd get more content than anything Bandai Namco has to or will offer  you with 112.33% cheaper price tag.-------------------------------------------------------------/// Pre-release Review ///With the way Ace Combat is going, this is one of the gems of arcade flight sim that sums up the entirety of AC and more with originality that's kept me months from playing Ace Combat: Infinity.It's still an Early Access, but even at that the AI aces pulls me to point-blank range without pulling off maneuvers where you'd need an omni-directional thrusters to pull off. All of that without the missiles being suckish.Guaranteed will be better than AC. â/infinity//// After Release (Per July 5 2015) ////After playing halfway through the Hollow Thunder campaign (fully-voiced, full-fledged original campaign), I don't have much crashes as others have claimed. I find this great, considering it's original EA release was full of bugs you can't seem to play it after 5 minutes.There are only 2 crashes during my 5 hour gameplay; the last one being me modding some stuff and testing it out; I find this release actually better than any arcade flight games on Steam right now. Vector Thrust gives you total freedom over the game, play it however you want.Although, keep in mind that VT was built with modding around its centre, thus some people who just wanted constant stream of contents without making one might not be entertained as much. VT has the core gameplay of Ace Combat, yet gives you the "Debug" side of it; making you see and control the developer side of the game. If you think you can feel fine with modding (even as simple as making skins), you'd be having a great time with VT's easy-to-learn modding system.The majority of negative reviews I've seen are mostly people who can't make contents and whine instead of helping those who does make them. You can check Moddb.com for the majority of free addons that expand the game two-fold; maybe helping them out too by giving feedbacks. You'd be surprised that some of the bugs you have (if you still have) can be easily fixed by contacting the community.
